    "summary": "Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen discovered X-rays on 8 November 1895 while experimenting with cathode ray tubes at the University of Würzburg. Noticing that a fluorescent screen in his laboratory was glowing despite being shielded from the cathode ray tube, he deduced that a previously unknown type of ray was passing through solid materials. He named them X-rays for their unknown nature.\n\nRöntgen's subsequent experiments revealed the extraordinary properties of X-rays: they could pass through human soft tissue but were partially blocked by bone and metal, producing images of internal structures on photographic film. His first X-ray image — of his wife's hand showing her bones and her wedding ring — was published in January 1896 and immediately caused a worldwide sensation. Within months, X-ray machines were being used in hospitals across Europe and America.\n\nThe medical applications were immediately obvious and revolutionary. Surgeons could now see bone fractures, locate bullets and foreign objects in the body, and diagnose internal conditions without surgery. The discovery accelerated the development of nuclear physics — the investigation of what was happening inside atoms to produce such radiation — and contributed to the broader revolution in physics around 1900 that included radioactivity (discovered by Henri Becquerel months after Röntgen's announcement) and eventually quantum mechanics. Röntgen received the first Nobel Prize in Physics in 1901 for his discovery, and the unit of radiation exposure was named the roentgen in his honor.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-ray",
